We call this wee drop the lost scott, named after the highland bull, scott, who is now to be found wandering far from the bonnie hills and glens from where he grew up. As lost as he may be, legend has it that if ye hold this can up to yer ear ye can hear the Scottish wilds and indeed the blended scotch whisky inside. But gonnae no dae that, for that is a terrible way to enjoy our crackin' blended scotch whisky and cola. Beyond the highland tale, the actual story behind scot has been lost in time. To be honest, we dinnae even know how you've got hold of the can yer holding. Lost Scott. Aye. Ye Found One.

It’s a sparkling drop of low to medium sweetness that exhibits a pithy lemon aroma and flavour wit

AdditionalDetails.Name: webdescriptionshort
AdditionalDetails.Value:
Take a moment to honour the legacy of the Monsutā with an immense tasty refreshment. A take on the crisp and refreshing Japanese Shōchū highball known as the Chūhai, this delicious blend of vodka, Shōchū spirit, soda and lemon is bursting with zesty refreshment.

This Monsutā Chūhai uses a traditional Okinawan Shōchū called Awamori, which is indigenous and unique to Okinawa, Japan.

It’s a sparkling drop of low to medium sweetness that exhibits a pithy lemon aroma and flavour with a clean, crisp taste and a slightly savoury lemon finish.

Built for sunlit afternoon sessions, sipping with friends, this delicious spritz can be enjoyed straight from the can or poured over ice.

AdditionalDetails.Name: webdescriptionshort
AdditionalDetails.Value: Aye. It sure is a blended scotch whisky and cola in a can yer eyeing. We call this wee drop the lost scott, named after the highland bull, scott, who is now to be found wandering far from the bonnie hills and glens from where he grew up. As lost as he may be, legend has it that if ye hold this can up to yer ear ye can hear the Scottish wilds and indeed the blended scotch whisky inside. But gonnae no dae that, for that is a terrible way to enjoy our crackin' blended scotch whisky and cola. Beyond the highland tale, the actual story behind scot has been lost in time. To be honest, we dinnae even know how you've got hold of the can yer holding. Lost Scott. Aye. Ye Found One.

A combination of Echuca Distillery’s High St Dry Gin, Gold Agave Spirit, Coconut Flower Spirit, Lemon Myrtle Vodka & Orange Liqueur. 100% handcrafted, produced and distilled in Echuca.
Makes a great Long Island Iced Tea:
  • 60ml Echuca Distillery Long Island Iced Tea Cocktail Spirit
  • 15ml Lime Juice
  • 60ml Cola (we prefer coke but any cola will do)
  • Ice
  • Lime Wedge for garnish.
Method:
  1. Fill Cocktail Shaker with ice.
  2. Add spirit & lime juice into Shaker & shake vigorously until frothy.
  3. Fill a Highball Glass with ice.
  4. Add cola.
  5. Strain contents of Shaker on top.
  6. Garnish with Lime. (wedge or wheel)
You will need to supply:
  • Cocktail Shaker
  • Ice Cubes
  • Cola
  • Lime Juice
  • Lime for Garnish

Hints of coffee liqueur elevate the richness, ensuring each sip carries a velvety texture and a sumptuous finish. Nestled within a sophisticated black display box adorned with an embossed stamp, the packaging exudes a timeless elegance. Espresso Martini History
What do the Sex Pistols, Margaret Thatcher and the Espresso Martini have in common?Well, we don’t know if all three were ever in the same bar at the same time, but we do know they all found fame (and some say notoriety) in 1980s London.
There are several claims for the origin of the Espresso Martini. The more common claim was created at Freds Club, a Soho bar in the late 80s by bartender Dick Bradsell, for a young model who wanted something to “wake me up and f**k me up”. We can’t think of a drink that better embodies the spirit of London. With many variations, this perfect recipe combines Vodka, Cold Brew Coffee Liquor, Espresso Coffee Extract, and sugar cane. It’s an ideal cocktail for those who need an extra shot of life to make it through the night.
Serving Suggestions
To serve, fill a cocktail shaker with ice, pour Dr Onyx Espresso Martini and shake vigorously. Strain into a chilled martini glass and garnish with fresh coffee beans.
Ingredients
Vodka, Coffee Liqueur, Coffee Espresso, Sugar Cane Syrup, Water.
Volume
100ml, 16% Alcohol, Approx. 1.3 Standard Drinks.100ml, 16% Alcohol, Approx. 1.3 Standard Drinks.

Experience the timeless allure of our 6-Pack of Old Fashioned cocktails, meticulously crafted to honor a classic. Every bottle reveals a captivating symphony of robust whiskey, a hint of sugar, and the aromatic embrace of bitters, crowned with a citrus twist. This blend results in a cocktail that's both bold in flavor and smooth in finish, capturing the very essence of a bygone era.
The drink's rich, amber elegance is accentuated within a beautifully contoured glass bottle, encapsulating its majesty. For the true connoisseur, our Old Fashioned set represents a harmonious fusion of taste, tradition, and artistry.
Old Fashioned History
The Old Fashioned is said to have been first created at the Pendennis Club, a famous gentlemen's club in Louisville, Kentucky in 1881 in honour of Colonel James E. Pepper – famed bourbon distiller, who then introduced it to New York high society during his frequent visits to the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel bar in New York. They clearly embraced it, given how the infamous ‘Mad Men’ had such a taste for it 80 years later in the 1960s Manhattan advertising scene. The Old Fashioned has had a makeover or two over its time. But this smooth, bitter, sweet simplicity of Straight Bourbon Whiskey, traditional Bitters, and sugar cane syrup is a tonic that Don Draper himself would approve of.
Serving Suggestions
Serve Dr Onyx Old Fashioned gently swirled in a short glass over ice, with a twist of orange zest. Pinch the zest so the oils spray over the drink before dropping it into the glass.
Ingredients
Bourbon Whiskey, Sugar Cane Syrup, Bitters, Water.
Volume
100ml, 30% Alcohol, Approx. 2.4 Standard Drinks.

Manhattan:
The first skyscrapers began to change the skyline of Manhattan Island in the 1880s, just as NYC’s Manhattan Club claims they created the first Manhattan cocktail.  And it’s making just as big an impact 140 or so years later, capturing all the glamour and excitement of New York City in a glass. Step into an era of sophistication with our 'Speakeasy' Dry Martini. This 500ml hand-crafted gem offers a harmonious blend of premium gin and dry vermouth, balanced to perfection, evoking the elegance of the Roaring Twenties. Each sip reveals subtle botanical undertones, elevated by a hint of citrus, culminating in a crisp, refined finish.
Encased in a gracefully contoured glass bottle, the martini's clarity and shimmer shine through, paying homage to its storied history. The luxurious packaging, with its classic black theme and embossed details, adds a touch of opulence, making this Dry Martini not only a delightful drink but a visual feast.
Dry Martini History
Ernest Hemingway described the Martini best “I’ve never tasted anything so cool and clean...They make me feel civilised”. It was James Bond’s drink of choice where the catchphrase "shaken, not stirred" was introduced in Diamonds Are Forever (1956), and then incorrectly referred to as "stirred, not shaken" in You Only Live Twice (1967), to Bond's response "Perfect".
The Martini rose to prominence during the 1950s and 60s when the ‘three-martini lunch’ was widespread. Whilst the stance on workplace drinking might have changed, our affection for the Martini hasn’t. An excellent tonic for those wanting to step back to a more sophisticated time.
Serving Suggestions
To serve, pour Dr Onyx Dry Martini into a mixing glass filled with ice. Stir, and strain into a chilled martini glass. Garnish with an olive or citrus zest, squeeze to release the oils over the glass before you dropping it in.
Ingredients
Dry Gin, Dry Vermouth, Bitters, Water.
Volume
500ml, 30% Alcohol, Approx. 12 Standard Drinks.

Transport your senses to the glamorous era of the 1920s with our ‘Speakeasy’ Negroni cocktail. Expertly mixed in a 500ml measure, this hand-crafted concoction artfully balances the bitterness of premium gin with the sweet vermouth and the complex, herbaceous notes of Campari. This harmonious blend offers a taste that is both robust and refreshing, echoing the vivacity of the times it celebrates.
Encased in a meticulously designed glass bottle that radiates sophistication, the ruby-red hue of the cocktail invites admiration. Negroni History
There are many stories about who created the first Negroni. We like to believe it originated in Florence, Italy in 1919 when Count Camillo Negroni asked for a stronger version of his favourite cocktail – the Americano (Campari, Red Vermouth and soda water). The bartender replaced the traditional soda for gin, and the world-famous aperitif was born.
The definition of sophistication and simplicity – the Negroni is a tonic for those who would rather be sitting in a local bar during what the Italians refer to as ‘aperitivo hour’.
Serving Suggestions
Serve Dr Onyx Negroni swirled, not shaken in a short glass over ice. Traditionally garnished with a slice of orange or the preferred blood orange adding a more dramatic fragrance, and a sweet and tart flavour.
Ingredients
Dry Gin, Campari, Vermouth, Orange Bitters, Water.
Volume
500ml, 22% Alcohol, Approx. 9.0 Standard Drinks.

Samai Distillery started back in 2014, using the highest quality molasses from local sugar cane to produce their rums along with drops of Cambodian honey. A combination of pot and column distillation is used, the pot still giving a rich spirit full of character and the column providing a light rum to blend.




The rums are aged in a combination of French oak, American Bourbon barrels and Spanish sherry casks to create a seamless blend of mature flavours.
Nose: Sweet notes of vanilla, molasses and honey.
Palate: Hints of oak, vanilla and honey are married together and a slight persisting sweetness.
Overall: A great everyday drinking rum for those who like those classic rum flavours with a Cambodian twist.

About Xicaru Mezcal: Xicaru, the Zapotec word for beautiful, reflects Fernando Santibanez's desire to share a traditionally produced mezcal that is approachable and distinct. Using his grandmother’s recipe, Fernando makes small batches of Xicaru Mezcal with time-honoured methods at a Palenque in Matatlan, Oaxaca. This mezcal showcases the 100% Agave espadin from which it’s made. Its natural smoky flavour is derived by cooking the agave in a conical stone oven on mesquite and ocote, woods native to Oaxaca.
